<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,631,898]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Narrow buccal and pharyngeal tubes divided by the drop. Three rod-shaped macroplacoids, microplacoid and septulum present within the pharyngeal bulb. Macroplacoid length increasing from the first to the third one. Mean body size, among the 
<specimenCount box="[536,695,752,778]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="generic">
<number box="[536,565,752,778]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="65.0">65</number>
specimens
</specimenCount>
collected, was 
<number box="[874,918,752,778]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="388.0">388</number>
μm (SD 
<number box="[1025,1057,752,778]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="63.0">63</number>
), range 
<number box="[1150,1275,752,778]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="396.0" valueMax="528.0" valueMin="264.0">264 to 528</number>
μm. The species has been cited for Europe, Asia, 
<collectingCountry box="[584,685,792,818]" name="United States of America" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">America</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[741,863,792,818]" name="Antarctica" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Antarctica</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ramazzotti" box="[878,1207,792,818]" pageId="17" pageNumber="29" refString="Ramazzotti, G. &amp; Maucci, W. (1983) Il phylum Tardigrada. III edizione riveduta e aggiornata. Memorie dell'Istituto Italiano di Idrobiologia Dott. Marco de Marchi, 41, 1 - 1012." type="journal article" year="1983">
Ramazzotti &amp; Maucci 
<number box="[1145,1207,792,818]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1983.0">1983</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="McInnes" box="[1219,1392,792,818]" pageId="17" pageNumber="29" refString="McInnes, S. J. (1994) Zoogeographic distribution of terrestrial / freshwater tardigrades from current literature. Journal of Natural History, 28, 257 - 352." type="journal article" year="1994">
McInnes 
<number box="[1329,1392,792,818]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1994.0">1994</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). In the Iberian Peninsula, it has been recorded for 
<collectingCountry box="[698,765,832,858]" name="Spain" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Spain</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Guil" box="[781,906,832,858]" pageId="17" pageNumber="29" refString="Guil, N. (2002) Diversity and distribution of tardigrades (Bilateria, Tardigrada) from the Iberian Peninsula, Balearic Islands and Chafarinas Islands. Graellsia, 58 (2), 75 - 94." type="journal article" year="2002">
Guil 
<number box="[842,906,832,858]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[925,1294,832,857]" class="Eutardigrada" family="Hypsibiidae" genus="Diphascon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Parachela" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Tardigrada" rank="species" species="pingue" subGenus="Diphascon">
